Data Science Pipeline Tutorial - Analyzing a COVID-19 Dataset¶

Jonathan Probert, Akash Shetty, Selena Xiao¶

Introduction¶

The COVID-19 pandemic has impacted the world for over a year now, as of the making of this tutorial. Millions of lives have been lost, and even more have contracted this disease. By looking at the data relating to COVID and countries around the world, we can determine how to best react to, prepare for, and eventually eliminate COVID. In this tutorial, we will go through the data science pipeline, including data scraping, cleaning, exploration through visualization, hypothesis testing, and machine learning, in order to gain some insight from this dataset.

Data Scraping¶

Data scraping is the process where we import data that isnt necessarily neatly formatted from a website into a formatted file that we can easily parse through. The dataset that we are using is located at https://covid.ourworldindata.org/data/owid-covid-data.csv and is already in csv format.

It updates daily, so we are using the dataset as it was downloaded on May 03, 2021.

Data Cleaning¶

Data cleaning is the process where we clean up the collected data. Cleaning up can include the following:

  1. Accounting for any data scraping errors. If the online dataset doesnt include column names, then we would have to add those when creating our DataFrame

  2. The dataset might be incomplete. Some rows may not have a value in every column. How this missing data is represented depends on the dataset. Looking at the documentation of the online dataset is the best way to determine what constitutes missing. Once we know that, we can then change those values to NaN, which NumPy uses to represent a missing value - https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/constants.html#numpy.NAN We perform this change because when the library functions that we use to analyze this data is programmed to skip over the NaN values. In our data, missing values are already written as NaN.

Through data scraping, we have a bunch of data in an organized DataFrame with labelled columns. But this DataFrame contains a TON of information that we may not need. The dataset's README at https://github.com/owid/covid-19-data/tree/master/public/data shows that it contains daily records for cases, deaths, and health statistics for every country in the world. Besides daily information for each country, the data also contains daily information for each continent as well as the entire world.

We remove the rows that contain a non-country value as its location. This is represented in the data as an iso_code starting with OWID.

In [39]:
# deleting references to world data (wrl)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_WRL']

# # deleting references to Africa (afr)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_AFR']

# # deleting references to Asia (asi)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_ASI']

# # deleting references to Europe and EU (EUR and EUN)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_EUR']
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_EUN']

# # deleting references to North America (nam)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_NAM']

# # deleting references to Oceania (oce)
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_OCE']

# # deleting references to South America (sam)  
data = data[data.iso_code != 'OWID_SAM']

Additionally, for initial data exploration, we will only be looking at cases and deaths for the top 50 most populous countries on May 3rd 2021. We drop the unneeded columns.

    avg_new_cases.append(data[data.location == row['location']]['new_cases'].mean())

top_50['avg_new_deaths'] = avg_new_deaths

# remove new cases and new deaths columns as they are only for may 3
top_50= top_50.drop(columns=['new_deaths', 'new_cases'])
# remove date because data spans more than just this date
top_50 = top_50.drop(columns=['date'])

Data Exploration and Visualization¶

Data exploration is an important step because it provides an idea on relationships that might exist within the data. This helps guide our data analysis with hypothesis testing and machine learning. One main way of exploration is by actually visualizing this data through plots.

The data contains a column dedicated to total deaths for each country. Let's start by visualizing that.

In [41]:
# Plotting the total deaths of the top 50 most populated countries from covid-19

While looking at total deaths and cases can give insight into how much a country has been affected, it doesn't take into account the population of that country. For example, Country A may have only 1000 cases, which is miniscule when compared to 1 million cases in Country B. However, Country A may have a population of 10000, while Country B has a population of a billion. In that case, Country A has a larger proportion of its population that has been impacted by COVID.

Even though we are only looking at the top 50 most populous countries, this difference between totals and population is still important. The most populous in our top_50 list, China, has a 1.4 billion population, while the least populous, Venezuela is 28 million. We think this difference in population is large enough, so let's visualize proportion of deaths and cases next.

In [43]:
# adds the proportion of total cases and total deaths compared to the population of the country to top_50
proportion_of_total_cases = []
proportion_of_total_deaths = []
for index, row in top_50.iterrows():
    proportion_of_total_cases.append(row['total_cases'] / row['population'])
    proportion_of_total_deaths.append(row['total_deaths'] / row['population'])
    
top_50['total_cases / population'] = proportion_of_total_cases
top_50['total_deaths / population'] = proportion_of_total_deaths
top_50

Hypothesis Testing¶

Now we move onto Hypothesis Testing. Hypothesis Testing is typically used to test your data for specific results. In most cases of Hypothesis Testing, you have two hypotheses that you want to use to compare data: The null hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis, which contradict each other. You want to set up your data in a way that you will reject your null hypothesis. This basically means that the null hypothesis is your default, your data is assumed to be true to the null hypothesis. If you reject your null hypothesis it means you have enough data to conclude that the null hypothesis is not true and the data favors the alternative hypothesis. To accurately check if your data rejects the null hypothesis we need to use a significance level. This is a certain value that is used to check whether or not to reject, typically this number is set to 0.05, but 0.01 and 0.10 are also used. Depending on the type of Hypothesis Test that you are using there are certain ways find a value called the p-value. This is the value that you calculate and compare to the significance level. If the p-value is less than the significance level than we reject the null hypothesis, if it is greater(or equal to) we fail to reject it. Here is more on Hypothesis Testing: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing

Now lets look at our data.

Our graphs from the total cases and deaths have a similar outcome as those of the average new cases and deaths. Since this is the case it will be the case that the proportion of total deaths and total cases to population will more accurately represent how well certain countries did compared to others. Of the countries with the highest proportions, we will conduct hypothesis tests with the following hypothesis test formulas:

$$significance\,level\, \alpha = 0.05$$\begin{align} H_0 & : p_1 = p_2 \qquad \\ H_a & : p_1 \ne p_2 \qquad \end{align}

Where p1 and p2 are the proportions of cases or deaths to population for countries 1 and 2.

If we reject the null hypothesis it means that country 1 has a different proportion of cases/deaths to population, and if this happens it means that the country with the higher proportion has been hit harder by COVID-19.

The formula below is what the following code is using to find the text statistic Z. The Z value is then used to find the pvalue using a standard normal z-table:(provided in the link) https://www.math.arizona.edu/~rsims/ma464/standardnormaltable.pdf

In [48]:
# sort by cases proportion
sort_by_cases_prop = top_50.sort_values(by=['total_cases / population'], ascending=False)

new = {}
hypothesis_of_cases = pd.DataFrame(new, columns = ['country1', 'proportion1', 'country2', 'proportion2', 'pvalue', 'result'])
# loops through the list of countries sorted highest proportion to lowest comparing the current index to the one below it.
for i in range(49):
    sig = 0.05 # for 2 sided
    
    #gets the total cases and populations for the current country and the country with the next highest proportion to compare
    sample_succ_a, sample_size_a = (sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i]['total_cases'], sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i]['population'])
    sample_succ_b, sample_size_b = (sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i+1]['total_cases'], sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i+1]['population'])
    #creates an array of the total_cases and populations of both countries
    successes = np.array([sample_succ_a, sample_succ_b])
    samples = np.array([sample_size_a, sample_size_b])
    
    #uses the stated formula for Z to find the stat value from the previous data and uses a normal z table to find the pvalue
    stat, pvalue = proportions_ztest(count=successes, nobs=samples,  alternative='two-sided')
    
    #compares the obtained pvalue and compares it to our significance level.
    if pvalue >= sig: reject_check = 'fail to reject null hypothesis'
    else: reject_check = 'reject null hypothesis'
    
    #create new row to add to dataframe
    result_to_add = {'country1':sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i]['location'], 'proportion1':sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i]['total_cases / population'],
                    'country2':sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i+1]['location'], 'proportion2':sort_by_cases_prop.iloc[i+1]['total_cases / population'],
                    'pvalue':pvalue,'result':reject_check}
    
    #append to dataframe
    hypothesis_of_cases = hypothesis_of_cases.append(result_to_add, ignore_index=True)
    
hypothesis_of_cases

Machine Learning¶

In our Data Exploration and Visualization, we looked at average new cases as a way to "predict" how cases will increase in the future for each country.

A more robust way to actually predict future case counts is through machine learning. Due to the amount of countries in our sample lets look at the top three countries (China, India, USA) and the bottom three countries (Yemen, Nepal, Venezuala) within the 50 countries we have already selected. To predict the daily cases for the six countries we are looking at we are going to use a polynomial regression for the six countries as opposed to a linear regression. Using Polynomial regression is more appropriate due to the nature of the graphs because of the many critical points within each of the daily cases graphs. For the Polynomial regression, lets have the regression completed with a degree of n = 4.

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures 

# gathering the data for the China daily cases as well as the days since the outbreak started 
chn_data = chn_data.iloc[1:]
china_cases = np.array(chn_data["new_cases"]).reshape(-1, 1)
china_days = np.arange(chn_data.shape[0]).reshape(-1, 1) 

# training the poly regression model for the china data 
china_poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree = 4)
china_x_poly = china_poly.fit_transform(china_days)
china_lin = LinearRegression() 
china_lin.fit(china_x_poly, china_cases)


plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
plt.plot(china_days, china_lin.predict(china_poly.fit_transform(china_days)), label = "Regression Model Prediction")
plt.plot(china_days, china_cases, label = "Daily Cases") 
plt.title("Daily Covid-19 Cases in China since the outbreak")
plt.xlabel("Days Since Covid Arrived in China")
plt.ylabel("Daily Cases")
plt.legend() 
plt.show()

For the Poly Regression model for China, it appears that it can predict the future cases with some accuracy but earlier, before day 100, the regression model is a poor representation of the Covid daily cases within China. Perhaps a larger degree for the poly regression model will solve this misrepresenatation.

Final Thoughts¶

In this tutorial, we analyzed the COVID-19 deaths and cases counts for the top 50 most populous countries.

In our data exploration section, we looked at total deaths/cases, proportion of deaths/cases, and average new deaths/cases. The graphs for totals and averages looked similar - a few countries looked like they were far more impacted by COVID than the rest of the countries. The proportion graphs took country population into account, and that resulted in the countries looking like they were more similarly impacted.

In hypothesis testing, we found that a larger proportion of deaths and cases often meant that the country was more severely impacted by COVID. This result is represented by rejecting the null hypothesis. There were 3 exceptions in cases - Kenya vs Ghana, Egypt vs Ethiopia, Ethiopia vs Mozambique and there was 1 exception in deaths - Vietnam vs Tanzania, where we failed to reject the null hypothesis.

We used machine learning to predict daily new case counts for the top 3 and bottom 3 populous countries in our data, specifically poly regression with n = 4. Our results showed that the regression was not always representative and couldn't always predict the future case counts for most countries. However, it could most accurately predict Venezuela and India. Additional work in this area such as increasing the poly regression degree may improve the prediction for other countries.

We hope this tutorial provided insight on the data science pipeline and on how countries are impacted by COVID-19. This tutorial is not meant to be comprehensive of all the analysis that could be performed on this dataset. Additional analysis can and should be performed for additional insights.
